PART 1: Prepare Your Project
📁 Step 1: Create your project folder

Example:

myapp/
 ├── app.py
 ├── requirements.txt
 └── Dockerfile
🐍 Example app.py
print("Hello from Docker + Jenkins!")
📦 requirements.txt
# keep empty or add packages if needed
🐳 Step 2: Create Dockerfile
FROM python:3.9

WORKDIR /app

COPY . .

RUN pip install -r requirements.txt

CMD ["python", "app.py"]
🧪 Step 3: Test Docker Locally (IMPORTANT)
cd myapp
docker build -t myapp .
docker run myapp

If this fails → Jenkins will also fail. Fix here first.

📤 PART 2: Push Code to GitHub

Use GitHub

git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"

git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/docker_demo.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main
🐳 PART 3: Push Image to Docker Hub (Manual First)

Use Docker Hub

Step 1: Login
docker login
Step 2: Tag
docker tag myapp yourusername/myapp:v1
Step 3: Push
docker push yourusername/myapp:v1

✔️ Confirm on Docker Hub website

🔐 PART 4: Add Docker Hub Credentials in Jenkins

Use Jenkins

Steps:
Open Jenkins → http://localhost:8080

Go to:

Manage Jenkins → Credentials → Global → Add Credentials
Add:
Kind: Username & Password
ID: dockerhub-creds
Username: your Docker Hub username
Password: Access Token (NOT password)
🔑 How to Get Docker Token
Login to Docker Hub

Go to:

Account Settings → Security → Access Tokens
Generate token
📄 PART 5: Create Jenkinsfile (MOST IMPORTANT)

Create a file named Jenkinsfile in your project root:

pipeline {
    agent any

    environment {
        IMAGE_NAME = "yourusername/myapp"
        TAG = "v1"
    }

    stages {

        stage('Clone Repo') {
            steps {
                git 'https://github.com/your-username/docker_demo.git'
            }
        }

        stage('Build Docker Image') {
            steps {
                script {
                    sh 'docker build -t $IMAGE_NAME:$TAG .'
                }
            }
        }

        stage('Login to Docker Hub') {
            steps {
                withCredentials([usernamePassword(
                    credentialsId: 'dockerhub-creds',
                    usernameVariable: 'USER',
                    passwordVariable: 'PASS'
                )]) {
                    sh 'echo $PASS | docker login -u $USER --password-stdin'
                }
            }
        }

        stage('Push Image') {
            steps {
                sh 'docker push $IMAGE_NAME:$TAG'
            }
        }
    }
}
⚙️ PART 6: Create Jenkins Pipeline Job
Jenkins Dashboard → New Item
Enter name → select Pipeline
Configure:
Pipeline → Pipeline script from SCM
SCM → Git
Repo URL → your GitHub repo
Script Path → Jenkinsfile

Save.

▶️ PART 7: Run Build

Click Build Now

✔️ Expected stages:

Clone
Build
Login
Push
🔁 PART 8: AUTOMATE using Webhook

Use ngrok

Step 1: Start ngrok
ngrok http 8080

You’ll get URL like:

https://abc123.ngrok.io
Step 2: Add Webhook in GitHub

Go to your repo → Settings → Webhooks → Add webhook

Payload URL:
https://abc123.ngrok.io/github-webhook/
Content type: application/json
Event: Just push
Step 3: Enable in Jenkins

In job config:
✔️ Enable:

GitHub hook trigger for GITScm polling
🔥 FINAL FLOW
You push code → GitHub
GitHub webhook → Jenkins
Jenkins:
Builds Docker image
Logs into Docker Hub
Pushes image
